    {
      "id": "msg_0485e7c463a292010169cc280e2e748190958d28893f4d00da",
      "type": "message",
      "status": "completed",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "output_text",
          "annotations": [],
          "logprobs": [],
          "text": "Here\u2019s the relevant OpenAI docs page and section, then a concise summary of require_approval:\n\nSource\n- MCP and Connectors \u2192 Approvals (Responses API): https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/tools-connectors-mcp/#approvals\n\nSummary of require_approval for the MCP tool (Responses API)\n- What it controls: Whether the platform must request your explicit approval before a model can call a tool on a remote MCP server or connector (and therefore send data to it).\n- Default behavior: Approval is required by default before any data is shared with a connector or remote MCP server. When required, the Responses API emits an mcp_approval_request item; you must reply with a new Response containing an mcp_approval_response (approve: true/false, approval_request_id).\n- Configuration options:\n  - \"always\": Always require approval for tool calls to that MCP server (explicitly enforcing the default).\n  - \"never\": Never require approval for any tools on that MCP server (reduced latency; only do this if you trust the server).\n  - Object form (per-tool skipping): Set require_approval to an object specifying tool_names under never to skip approvals only for certain tools, while keeping approvals required for others. Example:\n    - require_approval: { \"never\": { \"tool_names\": [\"ask_question\", \"read_wiki_structure\"] } }\n- Recommended practice: Keep approvals on unless you fully trust the remote MCP server; approvals provide visibility and control over what data is sent. Optionally log what\u2019s being shared.\n\nSupporting snippets from the docs\n- \u201cBy default, OpenAI will request your approval before any data is shared with a connector or remote MCP server\u2026 A request for an approval to make an MCP tool call creates a mcp_approval_request item\u2026 You can then respond \u2026 by appending an mcp_approval_response item\u2026\u201d\n- \u201cIf and when you feel comfortable trusting a remote MCP server, you can choose to skip the approvals for reduced latency\u2026 set the require_approval parameter \u2026 to an object listing just the tools you\u2019d like to skip approvals for\u2026 or set it to the value \u2018never\u2019 to skip approvals for all tools\u2026\u201d (See: Approvals section linked above)"
        }
      ],
